### 5. FollowUp

Replaces the old `follow_up_date + reminderSent BOOLEAN` pattern from the PHP app.
A lead can have **multiple follow-ups** over its lifecycle.
Each follow-up tracks its own scheduled time, reminder state, and outcome independently.

| Field | Type | Notes |
|-------|------|-------|
| `id` | String (UUID) | PK |
| `leadId` | String (FK → Lead.id) | The lead this follow-up is for |
| `adminId` | String (FK → User.id) | **Denormalized from Lead** — kept for efficient dashboard queries without JOIN |
| `scheduledAt` | DateTime | When the follow-up is due |
| `status` | Enum (FollowUpStatus) | See enums below |
| `reminderSentAt` | DateTime? | Null = reminder not yet fired |
| `reminderChannel` | String? | "whatsapp" / "email" / "both" |
| `completedAt` | DateTime? | Set when status → COMPLETED |
| `snoozedUntil` | DateTime? | New target datetime if snoozed |
| `notes` | String? | What happened in this follow-up |
| `createdAt` | DateTime | Auto |
| `updatedAt` | DateTime | Auto |

**Why `adminId` is not redundant**: Dashboard query "show today's follow-ups for admin X" runs against FollowUp directly. Without `adminId` on FollowUp, every such query requires a JOIN through Lead. At scale this matters.

**Indexes**: `leadId`, `adminId`, `scheduledAt`, `status`

**Cascade**: deleted when parent Lead is deleted.

#### Access by Role

| Operation | SUPER_ADMIN | ADMIN |
|-----------|:-----------:|:-----:|
| Read all follow-ups | ✅ | ❌ |
| Read own follow-ups (`adminId` = self) | ✅ | ✅ |
| Create follow-up | ✅ | ✅ (own leads only) |
| Complete / Snooze / Cancel | ✅ | ✅ (own only) |

